Method 3) - // identical to c/c.js 
The "Compatibility" Hidden Method
This version uses a "blocking" technique. It’s less "fancy" but it forces the browser to treat it exactly like your original <script src="c/c.js"> tag while still keeping the filename hidden from a simple text search.
Replace your code with this:
<script>
  (function() {
    // 1. Obfuscate the path using simple charCodes
    // 99='/', 99='c', 46='.', 106='j', 115='s'
    var p = String.fromCharCode(99, 47, 99, 46, 106, 115); 
    
    // 2. Use document.write to "force" the script into the parsing stream
    // This is the most reliable way to mimic a standard <script> tag
    document.write('<script src="' + p + '" defer><\/script>');
  })();
</script>
Why this is the best fix for your Stamp System:
Immediate Injection: Unlike appendChild, document.write puts the script tag directly into the HTML as it is being read. This prevents the "missing UI" error because the browser "sees" the script at the same time it saw your original code.
String.fromCharCode: This is a great way to hide c/c.js. If a hacker searches for "c.js" or "atob", they won't find it. They would have to know to look for the character codes 99, 47....
Preserves defer: Since we are writing the tag directly, the defer attribute will work exactly as it did in your original version.
How to verify it's working:
If the UI still doesn't appear, try one quick test:
Right-click your page and select Inspect.
Click the Console tab.
If you see no red errors, the script is loading.
If the UI is still missing, look for a message that says Failed to load resource: the server responded with a status of 404. If you see that, we might need to check if your index.html and the /c/ folder are in the same directory.
Give the document.write version a try—it's usually the "magic bullet" for systems that break with standard dynamic injection.


